    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-06-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-06-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="636"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/339</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Secretary of the British Embassy</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Craigie</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-06-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 28, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Craigie</hi>: Let me acknowledge your personal
                    letter of June 22nd,<note n="15" xml:id="d636fn15">Not printed.</note> asking
                    whether I would be in a position to give you, <pb facs="0921" n="805"
                        xml:id="pg_805"/> unofficially and confidentially, the details in regard to
                    the amendments to the Federal Wireless contract, which that Company is seeking
                    to have made by the Chinese Government. I am very sorry to be compelled to reply
                    that I cannot at this time communicate the details of these amendments; but I am
                    happy to be able to assure you that they are not such as would substantially
                    affect the contract or be incompatible with any arrangements, on the basis of
                    the recommendations of the radio experts, dated February 4, 1922, which might
                    eventually be arrived at.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely young,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leland Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
